<edge source="concept.adjuration" target="concept.divine_name" id="edge.concept.adjuration.concerns_sacred_object.concept.divine_name">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.adjuration.concerns_sacred_object.concept.divine_name</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.adjuration</data>
  <data key="d8">Adjuration</data>
  <data key="d9">act_type</data>
  <data key="d10">concerns_sacred_object</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divine_name</data>
  <data key="d12">Divine Name</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-adjuration-concerns-sacred-object-concept-divine-name-st-ii-ii-q090-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q090.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A man who utters a promissory oath , swearing by his reverence for the Divine name, which he invokes in confirmation of his promise, binds himself to do what he has undertaken, and so orders himself unchangeably to do a certain thing. Now jus</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.adjuration" target="concept.sacred_thing" id="edge.concept.adjuration.concerns_sacred_object.concept.sacred_thing">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.adjuration.concerns_sacred_object.concept.sacred_thing</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.adjuration</data>
  <data key="d8">Adjuration</data>
  <data key="d9">act_type</data>
  <data key="d10">concerns_sacred_object</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sacred_thing</data>
  <data key="d12">Sacred Thing</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-adjuration-concerns-sacred-object-concept-sacred-thing-st-ii-ii-q090-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q090.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">hom he can compel on the strength of the oath they have taken. Therefore, if a man by invoking the name of God , or any holy thing, intends by this adjuration to put one who is not his subject under an obligation to do a certain thing, in the same way as he would bind himself by oath , suc</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.adoration" target="concept.divine_worship" id="edge.concept.adoration.directed_to.concept.divine_worship">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.adoration.directed_to.concept.divine_worship</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.adoration</data>
  <data key="d8">Adoration</data>
  <data key="d9">act_type</data>
  <data key="d10">directed_to</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divine_worship</data>
  <data key="d12">Divine Worship</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-adoration-directed-to-concept-divine-worship-st-ii-ii-q084-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q084.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As Damascene says (De Fide Orth. iv, 12), since we are composed of a twofold nature , intellectual and sensible, we offer God a twofold adoration; namely, a spiritual adoration, consisting in the internal devotion of the mind ; and a bodily adoration, which consists in an exterior humbling of the body. A</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.astrological_divination" target="concept.divination" id="edge.concept.astrological_divination.species_of.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.astrological_divination.species_of.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.astrological_divination</data>
  <data key="d8">Astrological Divination</data>
  <data key="d9">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d10">species_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-astrological-divination-species-of-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">rtain things. If one endeavor to know the future by observing the position and movements of the stars, this belongs to "astrologers," who are also called "genethliacs," because they take note of the days on which people are born. If one observe the movements and cries of birds or of any ani</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
