  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.vow" target="concept.promise_to_god" id="edge.concept.vow.concerns_sacred_object.concept.promise_to_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.vow.concerns_sacred_object.concept.promise_to_god</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d8">Vow</data>
  <data key="d9">act_type</data>
  <data key="d10">concerns_sacred_object</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.promise_to_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Promise to God</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-vow-concerns-sacred-object-concept-promise-to-god-st-ii-ii-q088-a001-resp | ann.concept-vow-concerns-sacred-object-concept-promise-to-god-st-ii-ii-q088-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a001.resp | st.ii-ii.q088.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A vow denotes a binding to do or omit some particular thing. Now one man binds himself to another by means of a promise, which is an act of the reason to which faculty it belongs to direct. For just as a man by commanding or praying , directs, in a fashion, what others are to do | rvice of God is the proper act of latria . Now, it is evident from what has been said above ( 1 and 2 ) that a vow is a promise made to God , and that a promise is nothing else than a directing of the thing promised to the person to whom the promise is made. Hence a vow is a directing of the thing</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.vow" target="concept.divine_worship" id="edge.concept.vow.directed_to.concept.divine_worship">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.vow.directed_to.concept.divine_worship</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d8">Vow</data>
  <data key="d9">act_type</data>
  <data key="d10">directed_to</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divine_worship</data>
  <data key="d12">Divine Worship</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-vow-directed-to-concept-divine-worship-st-ii-ii-q088-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">g of the thing promised to the person to whom the promise is made. Hence a vow is a directing of the thing vowed to the worship or service of God . And thus it is clear that to take a vow is properly an act of latria or religion.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.written_charm_observance" target="concept.superstitious_observance" id="edge.concept.written_charm_observance.species_of.concept.superstitious_observance">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.written_charm_observance.species_of.concept.superstitious_observance</data>
